    },
    {
        "cell-phones": "Cell-Phone"
    },
    {
        ", etc. Semiconductors for ICs are mass-produced. To create an ideal semiconducting material, chemical purity is paramount. Any small imperfection can have a drastic effect on how the semiconducting material behaves due to the scale at which the materials are used.     A high degree of crystalline perfection is also required, since faults in crystal structure  interfere with the semiconducting properties of the material. Crystalline faults are a major cause of defective semiconductor devices. The larger the crystal, the more difficult it is to achieve the necessary perfection. Current mass production processes use crystal ": null
    },
    {
        "ingots": "Ingot"
    },
    {
        " between  in diameter which are grown as cylinders and sliced into ": null
    },
    {
        "wafers": "Wafer"
    },
    {
        ".     There is a combination of processes that is used to prepare semiconducting materials for ICs. One process is called ": null
    },
    {
        "thermal oxidation": "Thermal Oxidation"
    },
    {
        ", which forms ": null
    },
    {
